Specific spots in `ui.rs` where it pays off immediately:\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/tui/ui.rs` lines 305-312, 386-392, 441-453, 616-624 — all popup inner layout declarations\n- Lines 32-44 — main layout split\n\nThe main caution: `constraints!` macro syntax uses `==N` for `Length`, `>=N` for `Min`, `%N` for `Percentage`. It is non-obvious to readers unfamiliar with it. For a 2-person project this is a minor doc/onboarding cost.\n\n---\n\n### `terminput` — Detailed Evaluation\n\n**Verdict: Not worth it for this project.**\n\n`terminput` provides a backend-agnostic input event abstraction (wraps crossterm, termion, etc.). The pitch is portability: write event handlers once, run on any backend.\n\n`reme` uses crossterm exclusively, has zero stated intent to support other backends, and its event handling is already clean and thin. The `event.rs` is 73 lines, and `app.rs` uses raw `KeyCode`/`KeyEvent`/`KeyModifiers` from crossterm directly. The gain would be zero portability benefit in practice, at the cost of:\n\n1. An extra abstraction layer that adds mapping overhead.\n2. A new dependency with its own release cadence.\n3. Type re-exports that could conflict when crossterm types appear in both `tui-textarea` (which takes `crossterm::event::Event`) and terminput's re-wrapped types.\n\nPoint 3 is real: `tui-textarea` already calls `Input::from(crossterm_event)`. Mixing terminput's event type with tui-textarea's API would require either conversions or forking the textarea integration. That is a net regression.\n\nCrossterm 0.28 is a solid, maintained library. There is no reason to abstract over it here.\n\n---\n\n### Remaining Libraries\n\n**`ansi-to-tui`**\n- Use case: convert ANSI-colored terminal output into ratatui `Text`.\n- Applicable? No. `reme` displays user messages from its own structured data (`msg.content` is a plain `String` from its own protocol). There is no ANSI color input pipeline. Irrelevant unless you add a terminal-emulator-style