            "command": "gh issue create \\\n  --title \"fix: replace blocking crossterm::event::poll with async EventStream\" \\\n  --milestone \"TUI Improvements\" \\\n  --label \"bug\" \\\n  --body \"$(cat <<'EOF'\n## Summary\n\n`event.rs:36` uses `crossterm::event::poll(tick_rate)` — a blocking syscall inside `tokio::spawn`. This occupies a tokio worker thread for the full 100ms timeout on every iteration.\n\n## Problem\n\n```rust\n// Current (event.rs):\ntokio::spawn(async move {\n    loop {\n        if event::poll(tick_rate).unwrap_or(false) { // <-- BLOCKING\n            match event::read() { ... }\n        } else {\n            sender.send(Event::Tick).ok();\n        }\n    }\n});\n```\n\n`crossterm::event::poll()` is a blocking syscall. Inside `tokio::spawn`, it ties up a worker thread for the full `tick_rate` duration (100ms) on every iteration. With the default tokio runtime (num_cpus workers), this silently degrades async throughput.\n\n## Solution\n\nUse crossterm's `event-stream` feature (async-native):\n\n```rust\nuse crossterm::event::EventStream;\nuse futures::StreamExt;\n\nlet mut reader = EventStream::new();\ntokio::spawn(async move {\n    loop {\n        tokio::select! {\n            event = reader.next() => {\n                match event {\n                    Some(Ok(CrosstermEvent::Key(key))) if key.kind == KeyEventKind::Press => {\n                        if sender.send(Event::Key(key)).is_err() { break; }\n                    }\n                    Some(Ok(CrosstermEvent::Resize(w, h))) => {\n                        if sender.send(Event::Resize(w, h)).is_err() { break; }\n                    }\n                    Some(Err(_)) => break,\n                    None => break,\n                    _ => {}\n                }\n            }\n            _ = tokio::time::sleep(tick_rate) => {\n                if sender.send(Event::Tick).is_err() { break; }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n});\n```\n\nRequires adding `event-stream` feature to crossterm in `Cargo.toml` and `futures` (or `futures-lite`) as a dependency.\n\n## Source\n\nIdentified by ratatui ecosystem analysis (`docs/analysis/2026-03-27-ratatui-ecosystem-analysis.md`), Zero-Dependency Fix #2. Pattern used by twitch-tui.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `event.rs` uses `EventStream` instead of `event::poll`\n- [ ] No blocking syscalls inside async context\n- [ ] All keyboard and resize events still work\n- [ ] `cargo test` and `cargo clippy` pass\nEOF\n)\" 2>&1",
