            "content": "# v0.6: LAN Relay — Design Spec\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-28\n**Milestone:** v0.6 — LAN Relay\n**Status:** Design (revised after independent review)\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nRoute messages through LAN peers during partial Internet outages. A node in Personal Relay mode accepts envelopes from peers, stores them in a relay outbox, and delivers via the full tiered system (Direct, Quorum, BestEffort) — not just forward-to-Quorum.\n\nKey insight: the relay queue is an \"outbox without crypto.\" It reuses the same TransportCoordinator, delivery state machine, and retry logic as the client outbox. The only difference: no `inner_bytes`, no re-encryption, no DAG tracking — just opaque `envelope_bytes` → tiered delivery.\n\n---\n\n## Design decisions\n\n| Decision | Outcome | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Relay outbox structure | Generalize `ClientOutbox` with `OutboxOwnership` | Less duplication than a separate RelayOutbox; delivery state machine is identical |\n| Shared delivery logic | Extract into `reme-relay` crate | Node and client both need TransportCoordinator + outbox tick + peer policy |\n| Node operating modes | Both Infrastructure + Personal Relay in v0.6 | Config toggle; different deployments need different behavior |\n| TrustLevel prerequisite | Yes, build first | Relay policy needs trust levels to make capability decisions |\n| Security hardening prerequisite | Yes (#102, #116) | Relay trusts discovery results; discovery must be hardened first |\n| Peer policy | Configurable trust thresholds, not hardcoded | Network benefits from open relay; privacy-conscious users restrict it |\n| Relay delivery | Full tiered (Direct + Quorum + BestEffort) | Relay node might discover the actual recipient on LAN |\n| Fine-grained relay routing | Deferred | \"Relay only to node X\", \"no direct for relayed\" — additive, not needed for v0.6 |\n| BLE tier assignment | Contextual: Direct, relay, or BestEffort | No \"BLE mesh protocol\" — BLE relay is the same model as LAN HTTP relay |\n| ack_secret KDF change | Deferred to v0.7 | Needed for re-encryption (FLAG_DETACHED); v0.6 doesn't re-encrypt |\n\n---\n\n## Crate extraction: `reme-relay`\n\n### Motivation\n\nPersonal Relay nodes need TransportCoordinator + outbox tick + peer policy — all currently in client-only code. Extracting a shared crate avoids duplication and keeps delivery logic in one place.\n\n### What moves where\n\n| Current location | What | Destination |\n|---|---|---|\n| `reme-core` Client | `process_urgent_retries()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `process_maintenance()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `tiered_outbox_tick()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `tiered_config` field | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| New | `RelayPolicy` + `TrustThreshold` | `reme-relay` |\n| New | `TrustLevel` enum | `reme-relay` (shared type, not in reme-storage) |\n| New | `TrustResolver` trait | `reme-relay` (reme-storage implements it) |\n| New | `OutboxOwnership` enum | `reme-outbox` |\n| `reme-core` Client | `prepare_message()`, crypto, DAG, tombstones | Stays in `reme-core` |\n| `apps/client/src/discovery/` | `DiscoveryController` | Stays in client app for v0.6; node #145 uses advertise-only mDNS |\n\n### Proposed crate graph\n\n```\nreme-relay (NEW — shared delivery engine + policy types)\n├── reme-transport (TransportCoordinator, targets, delivery config)\n├── reme-outbox (generalized: Own vs Relay entries)\n└── reme-discovery (mDNS, peer verification)\n    NOTE: does NOT depend on reme-storage directly.\n    TrustLevel lives here; TrustResolver trait decouples from storage.\n\nreme-core (Client API — crypto + user-facing logic)\n├── reme-relay (delivery engine)\n├── reme-encryption (encrypt/decrypt)\n├── reme-message (wire formats)\n├── reme-storage (implements TrustResolver)\n└── Client-specific: prepare_message(), send_text_tiered(), DAG tracking,\n    tombstone handling, message decryption\n\nreme-node-core (Node API — mailbox + relay)\n├── reme-relay (delivery engine) ← NEW dependency\n├── reme-storage (MailboxStore + implements TrustResolver)\n├── reme-message\n└── Node-specific: mailbox storage, operating mode toggle,\n    HTTP API handlers, gossip replication (Infrastructure mode)\n```\n\n`reme-relay` does NOT depend on `reme-storage`. The `TrustLevel` enum and `TrustResolver` trait live in `reme-relay`. Both `reme-core` and `reme-node-core` provide a `TrustResolver` implementation backed by their storage layer. This keeps the relay engine storage-agnostic.\n\n### TrustResolver trait\n\n```rust\n/// Trait for looking up a peer's trust level.\n/// Implemented by storage layers in both client and node.\npub trait TrustResolver: Send + Sync {\n    /// Look up trust level for a peer by PublicID.\n    /// Returns Stranger if the peer is not in contacts.\n    fn resolve_trust(&self, peer_id: &PublicID) -> TrustLevel;\n\n    /// Look up trust level for a peer by routing key.\n    /// Used when only routing_key is available (e.g., from OuterEnvelope).\n    /// Returns Stranger if no contact matches.\n    fn resolve_trust_by_routing_key(&self, routing_key: &RoutingKey) -> TrustLevel;\n}\n```\n\n### DeliveryEngine\n\n```rust\n/// Shared delivery engine used by both Client and Node (Personal Relay mode).\n/// Drives the outbox tick loop: urgent retries, maintenance refreshes, expiry.\npub struct DeliveryEngine<S: OutboxStore> {\n    coordinator: Arc<TransportCoordinator>,\n    outbox: Outbox<S>,\n    config: TieredDeliveryConfig,\n}\n\nimpl<S: OutboxStore> DeliveryEngine<S> {\n    /// Combined tick: expire messages, process urgent retries, run maintenance.\n    pub async fn tick(&self) -> Result<TickResult, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Process urgent retries for messages that haven't reached quorum.\n    pub async fn process_urgent_retries(&self) -> Result<Vec<RetryResult>, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Process maintenance refreshes for distributed messages.\n    pub async fn process_maintenance(&self) -> Result<usize, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Enqueue an envelope for relay delivery (no inner_bytes, no DAG).\n    /// Deduplicates on (routing_key, message_id) — idempotent.\n    pub fn enqueue_relay(\n        &self,\n        routing_key: RoutingKey,\n        message_id: MessageID,\n        envelope_bytes: &[u8],\n        ttl_ms: Option<u64>,\n    ) -> Result<OutboxEntryId, DeliveryError>;\n}\n```\n\nThe Client wraps DeliveryEngine and adds crypto (`prepare_message()` → `engine.outbox.enqueue()` with `Ownership::Own`). The Node uses `engine.enqueue_relay()` directly.\n\nNote: `ClientOutbox` is renamed to `Outbox` (or `DeliveryOutbox`) since it now serves both client and node.\n\n---\n\n## Contact model rework (#179)\n\n### TrustLevel enum\n\nDefined in `reme-relay` (shared type), not in `reme-storage`:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, PartialOrd, Ord, Serialize, Deserialize)]\n#[repr(u8)]\npub enum TrustLevel {\n    Stranger = 0,   // Auto-created from incoming message, or unknown peer\n    Known = 1,      // Manually added, not verified\n    Verified = 2,   // Identity confirmed (LAN challenge-response, QR, out-of-band)\n    Trusted = 3,    // User-designated trusted contact\n}\n```\n\n`PartialOrd`/`Ord` derived so threshold comparisons work naturally: `peer.trust_level >= policy.relay_for`.\n\n### Contact struct (in reme-storage)\n\n```rust\npub struct Contact {\n    pub id: i64,\n    pub public_id: PublicID,\n    pub routing_key: RoutingKey,      // derived from public_id, persisted for indexing\n    pub name: Option<String>,\n    pub trust_level: TrustLevel,\n    pub verified_at: Option<i64>,     // unix timestamp of last verification\n    pub created_at: i64,\n}\n```\n\n### Schema migration\n\n```sql\n-- Step 1: Add columns\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN routing_key BLOB;\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN trust_level INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0;\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN verified_at INTEGER;\n\n-- Step 2: Backfill existing contacts as Known (they were manually added)\nUPDATE contacts SET trust_level = 1;\n\n-- Step 3: Index for routing_key lookups (relay policy, message routing)\nCREATE INDEX idx_contacts_routing_key ON contacts(routing_key);\n```\n\nColumn default is `0` (Stranger) for new rows — auto-created contacts from incoming messages get Stranger. Existing rows are backfilled to `1` (Known) since they were manually added.\n\n### Integration points\n\n- `Client::add_contact()` — default `Known` for manual adds\n- Auto-created from incoming messages — `Stranger`\n- `DiscoveryController` verification success — upgrade to `Verified` + set `verified_at`\n- `Client::set_trust_level()` — user-initiated trust changes\n- `TrustResolver` impl in `reme-storage::Storage` — queries contacts table\n\n---\n\n## Peer capability policy\n\n### Three policy axes\n\n| Policy | Controls | Question it answers |\n|---|---|---|\n| `accept_from` | HTTP POST /api/v1/submit | \"Who can push envelopes into my mailbox?\" |\n| `relay_for` | Relay queue → TransportCoordinator | \"Whose envelopes do I forward via my transports?\" |\n| `direct_deliver` | Discovery → Direct tier registration | \"Whose messages do I route to discovered LAN peers?\" |\n\n`relay_for` and `direct_deliver` are independent axes. `relay_for` controls whether an envelope enters the delivery pipeline at all. `direct_deliver` controls whether discovered LAN peers are registered as Direct tier targets. A configuration of `relay_for = \"known+\"` with `direct_deliver = \"verified+\"` means: relay Known contacts' envelopes to Quorum infrastructure, but only attempt Direct delivery for Verified+ contacts (where identity is confirmed).\n\n### Configuration\n\n```toml\n[node]\nmode = \"infrastructure\"  # \"infrastructure\" or \"personal_relay\"\n\n[node.personal_relay]\n# Tiered delivery settings for relay outbox\nquorum = { count = 2 }\noutbox_enabled = true\nurgent_initial_delay_secs = 5\nurgent_max_delay_secs = 300\nmaintenance_interval_hours = 4\ntick_interval_secs = 5\n\n# Relay outbox limits\nmax_relay_entries = 10000\nmax_relay_bytes = 52428800  # 50 MiB\nrelay_max_ttl_hours = 168   # 7 days cap regardless of envelope TTL\n\n[node.personal_relay.policy]\n# Trust level thresholds (\"any\", \"known+\", \"verified+\", \"trusted\", \"none\")\naccept_from = \"any\"           # default: accept from everyone\nrelay_for = \"verified+\"       # default: relay for verified and trusted contacts\ndirect_deliver = \"verified+\"  # default: direct deliver for verified and trusted\n\n# Per-trust-level rate limits (requests per minute, 0 = unlimited)\n[node.personal_relay.rate_limits]\nstranger = 5\nknown = 30\nverified = 100\ntrusted = 0\n```\n\n`direct_deliver` replaces the current `auto_direct_known_contacts` boolean in discovery config.\n\n### Default policy table\n\n| TrustLevel | accept_from=any | relay_for=verified+ | direct_deliver=verified+ |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Stranger | Yes (rate-limited 5/min) | No | No |\n| Known | Yes (rate-limited 30/min) | No | No |\n| Verified | Yes (100/min) | Yes | Yes |\n| Trusted | Yes (unlimited) | Yes | Yes |\n\n### Trust resolution at submit time\n\nWhen a peer submits an envelope via HTTP POST `/api/v1/submit`, the node must determine the submitter's trust level:\n\n| Scenario | How identified | TrustLevel |\n|---|---|---|\n| Anonymous POST (no auth) | IP only, no identity | Stranger |\n| Signed replication header with known contact PublicID | Signature verification → contact lookup | Contact's TrustLevel |\n| Signed replication header with unknown PublicID | Valid signature but not in contacts | Stranger |\n| mDNS-discovered peer (identity verified) | Already verified via challenge-response, IP match | Contact's TrustLevel (Verified+) |\n\nFor v0.6, the primary relay path is mDNS-discovered peers where identity is already verified. Anonymous HTTP submissions default to Stranger. Signed replication headers (node-to-node auth) are an existing mechanism — the node extracts the source PublicID from the replication signature and looks it up in contacts.\n\n### RelayPolicy struct\n\n```rust\npub struct RelayPolicy {\n    pub accept_from: TrustThreshold,\n    pub relay_for: TrustThreshold,\n    pub direct_deliver: TrustThreshold,\n    pub rate_limits: PerTrustRateLimits,\n    pub max_relay_entries: usize,\n    pub max_relay_bytes: u64,\n    pub relay_max_ttl_ms: u64,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy)]\npub enum TrustThreshold {\n    None,         // disabled\n    Any,          // all peers including strangers\n    KnownPlus,    // Known, Verified, Trusted\n    VerifiedPlus, // Verified, Trusted\n    TrustedOnly,  // Trusted only\n}\n\nimpl TrustThreshold {\n    pub fn allows(&self, level: TrustLevel) -> bool {\n        match self {\n            Self::None => false,\n            Self::Any => true,\n            Self::KnownPlus => level >= TrustLevel::Known,\n            Self::VerifiedPlus => level >= TrustLevel::Verified,\n            Self::TrustedOnly => level >= TrustLevel::Trusted,\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Node operating modes (#23)\n\n### Behavior differences\n\n| Aspect | Infrastructure | Personal Relay |\n|---|---|---|\n| Inbound envelopes | Store in mailbox | Store in mailbox + enqueue in relay outbox |\n| Outbound delivery | Fire-and-forget gossip (`ReplicationClient`) | Tiered delivery via `DeliveryEngine` |\n| Persistence | Mailbox only | Mailbox + relay outbox |\n| Retry logic | None | Full 3-phase (urgent → distributed → confirmed) |\n| Discovery | Optional (mDNS for node-to-node) | Recommended (enables Direct tier relay) |\n| Use case | Public mailbox serving many users | Home server, personal relay, gateway |\n\n### Implementation\n\n```rust\nenum NodeMode {\n    Infrastructure {\n        replication: ReplicationClient,\n    },\n    PersonalRelay {\n        engine: DeliveryEngine<SqliteOutboxStore>,\n        policy: RelayPolicy,\n        trust: Arc<dyn TrustResolver>,\n    },\n}\n```\n\nOn envelope receipt:\n- **Infrastructure**: `mailbox.store()` + `replication.broadcast()` (fire-and-forget)\n- **Personal Relay**: `mailbox.store()` + policy check + `engine.enqueue_relay()` (persistent, tiered)\n\n---\n\n## Outbox generalization\n\n### OutboxOwnership\n\n```rust\npub enum OutboxOwnership {\n    /// Our own message — has inner_bytes for potential re-encryption (v1.0)\n    Own,\n    /// Relaying for someone else — opaque envelope only\n    Relay,\n}\n```\n\n### OutboxStore trait changes\n\nThe current `outbox_enqueue()` requires `PublicID` and `ContentId` — relay entries have neither (can't derive PublicID from RoutingKey, and ContentId is inside the encrypted InnerEnvelope).\n\nNew method added to the trait:\n\n```rust\n/// Add a relay entry to the outbox.\n///\n/// Unlike `outbox_enqueue`, this only requires routing_key and message_id\n/// (available from OuterEnvelope without decryption).\n/// inner_bytes is empty, content_id is zeroed.\nfn outbox_enqueue_relay(\n    &self,\n    routing_key: RoutingKey,\n    message_id: MessageID,\n    envelope_bytes: &[u8],\n    expires_at_ms: Option<u64>,\n) -> Result<OutboxEntryId, Self::Error>;\n```\n\n### Schema changes\n\n```sql\n-- Add ownership column\nALTER TABLE outbox_entries ADD COLUMN ownership INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0;\n-- 0 = Own, 1 = Relay\n\n-- Add routing_key column (relay entries don't have PublicID)\nALTER TABLE outbox_entries ADD COLUMN routing_key BLOB;\n-- Backfill from existing recipient PublicIDs\n```\n\nThe `recipient` (PublicID) column remains for Own entries. Relay entries set `recipient` to zeroed bytes and use `routing_key` for lookups. The `content_id` column uses zeroed bytes for relay entries.\n\n### PendingMessage changes\n\n```rust\npub struct PendingMessage {\n    pub id: OutboxEntryId,\n    pub recipient: Option<PublicID>,  // None for relay entries\n    pub routing_key: RoutingKey,      // always available (derived or from envelope)\n    pub content_id: Option<ContentId>, // None for relay entries\n    pub ownership: OutboxOwnership,\n    pub envelope_bytes: Vec<u8>,\n    pub inner_bytes: Vec<u8>,         // empty for relay entries\n    pub created_at_ms: u64,\n    pub expires_at_ms: Option<u64>,\n    pub expired_at_ms: Option<u64>,\n    pub attempts: Vec<TransportAttempt>,\n    pub next_retry_at_ms: Option<u64>,\n    pub confirmation: Option<DeliveryConfirmation>,\n    pub successful_targets: HashSet<TargetId>,\n    pub tiered_phase: TieredDeliveryPhase,\n}\n```\n\n### Relay-specific behavior\n\n- **No DAG tracking**: Relay entries don't update sender DAG state. `content_id` is None.\n- **No re-encryption**: `inner_bytes` is empty; can't re-encrypt for different transport.\n- **TTL from envelope**: Relay entries respect the OuterEnvelope's `ttl_hours` field, capped by `relay_max_ttl_hours` from policy config.\n- **Deduplication**: `enqueue_relay()` deduplicates on `(routing_key, message_id)`. If an entry already exists, returns the existing `OutboxEntryId` (idempotent).\n- **Backpressure**: `enqueue_relay()` checks `max_relay_entries` and `max_relay_bytes` limits. Returns error if limits exceeded — the HTTP handler returns 503 Service Unavailable.\n\n### Relay state machine (simplified 2-phase)\n\nRelay entries use a simplified state machine — they skip Phase 2 (Distributed/maintenance) since the relay node has no way to confirm recipient receipt:\n\n```\nPhase 1 (Urgent): Aggressive retry until quorum reached\n    │\n    ├─ Quorum reached → Phase 3 (Confirmed)\n    │   Relay responsibility satisfied: \"I got this to enough infrastructure nodes.\"\n    │\n    └─ TTL expired → Expired\n        Best-effort delivery exhausted.\n```\n\nThe relay node does NOT receive tombstones for others' messages — tombstones go to the original sender. There is no Phase 2 maintenance for relay entries because:\n1. The relay node can't confirm recipient receipt (no DAG visibility)\n2. Once quorum is reached, the infrastructure nodes are responsible for serving the message\n3. Periodic re-submission would waste bandwidth for messages the relay has no stake in\n\nImplementation: the `DeliveryEngine` checks `ownership` when transitioning phases. For `Relay` entries, quorum → Confirmed directly. For `Own` entries, the existing 3-phase flow applies.\n\n---\n\n## Relay flow (Personal Relay mode)\n\n```\nPeer submits envelope via HTTP POST /api/v1/submit\n    │\n    ├─ Resolve peer TrustLevel:\n    │   - mDNS-verified peer → contact's TrustLevel (Verified+)\n    │   - Signed replication header → contact lookup by PublicID\n    │   - Anonymous → Stranger\n    │\n    ├─ Rate limit check (per TrustLevel)\n    │   - Exceeded → 429 Too Many Requests\n    │\n    ├─ accept_from threshold check\n    │   - Below threshold → 403 Forbidden\n    │\n    ├─ Node stores in mailbox (existing behavior, for recipient to fetch)\n    │\n    └─ relay_for threshold check\n        │\n        ├─ Below threshold → done (stored locally only, not relayed)\n        │\n        └─ Passes → Backpressure check (max_relay_entries, max_relay_bytes)\n            │\n            ├─ Limits exceeded → stored locally, not relayed (503 if relay was the point)\n            │\n            └─ OK → DeliveryEngine.enqueue_relay(routing_key, message_id, envelope_bytes)\n                │   (deduplicates on routing_key + message_id)\n                │\n                └─ Outbox tick loop:\n                    ├─ Tier 1 Direct: recipient discovered on LAN? → deliver directly\n                    ├─ Tier 2 Quorum: forward to configured HTTP mailboxes / MQTT\n                    └─ Tier 3 BestEffort: fire-and-forget to LoRa/Meshtastic if available\n```\n\nIntermittent connectivity is handled naturally: if the relay node loses Internet, the outbox tick loop retries in Phase 1 with exponential backoff (5s → 10s → ... → 300s cap). When connectivity returns, queued relay entries are delivered. This matches the ROADMAP's \"message delivered when Bob reconnects to Internet\" scenario.\n\n---\n\n## DiscoveryController extraction\n\nFor v0.6, the `DiscoveryController` (peer matching, verification, target registration) stays in `apps/client/`. The node's mDNS support (#145) is advertise-only for v0.6 — the node broadcasts its presence but doesn't actively discover and verify peers.\n\nFull `DiscoveryController` extraction into `reme-discovery` (or `reme-relay`) is deferred to v0.7 when the node needs peer verification for BLE relay. For v0.6, the node's relay egress goes through configured Quorum targets and any manually configured peer endpoints, not auto-discovered peers.\n\n---\n\n## mDNS TXT record extension\n\nCurrent TXT schema: `v=1`, `rk=<routing_key_hex>`, `port=<http_port>`.\n\nv0.6 adds a `caps` key for capability advertisement:\n\n```\ncaps=relay          # accepts envelopes for relay\ncaps=relay,store    # accepts envelopes for relay + persistent storage\n```\n\nFormat: comma-separated capability tokens. Forward-compatible for v0.7+ when BLE relay capabilities are added.\n\n---\n\n## Security hardening prerequisites\n\n### #102: Enforce public_id on direct peers\n\nScope Tier 1 routing so that direct delivery only targets peers whose `public_id` matches the message's `routing_key`. Currently, a discovered peer could theoretically receive envelopes not addressed to them. The fix: `TransportCoordinator` checks `target.config().can_serve(&envelope.routing_key)` — already partially implemented, needs enforcement.\n\n### #116: Channel binding for identity challenge-response\n\nThe current LAN identity verification (`GET /api/v1/identity?challenge=<base64>`) proves that the peer controls the claimed identity key, but doesn't bind the proof to the transport channel (HTTP connection). An attacker on the same LAN could MITM the verification. Fix: include transport-layer binding (e.g., TLS session ID or ephemeral connection nonce) in the signed challenge response.\n\n---\n\n## Dependency graph\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n    subgraph \"Layer 0: Prerequisites\"\n        A179[\"#179 TrustLevel + Contact rework\"]\n        A102[\"#102 public_id enforcement\"]\n        A116[\"#116 channel binding\"]\n        A145[\"#145 node mDNS discovery\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 1: Foundation\"\n        B1[\"reme-relay crate extraction\"]\n        B2[\"Outbox generalization (Own vs Relay)\"]\n        B75[\"#75 Peer capability policy\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 2: Relay\"\n        C23[\"#23 Node operating modes\"]\n        C2[\"Relay queue ingress\"]\n        C3[\"Relay queue egress (tiered)\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 3: Integration\"\n        D1[\"Integration tests\"]\n        D2[\"Documentation\"]\n    end\n\n    A179 --> B1\n    A179 --> B2\n    A179 --> B75\n    A102 --> B1\n    A116 --> B1\n    A145 --> C23\n    B1 --> C23\n    B2 --> C2\n    B75 --> C2\n    B75 --> C3\n    C23 --> C2\n    C23 --> C3\n    C2 --> D1\n    C3 --> D1\n    D1 --> D2\n```\n\n---\n\n## Deferred from v0.6\n\n- **ack_secret deterministic KDF** — needed for re-encryption in v0.7, not for v0.6 relay\n- **FLAG_DETACHED re-encryption** — v0.7 when BLE arrives\n- **Fine-grained relay routing** — \"relay only to node X\", \"no direct for relayed messages\"\n- **Relay-specific rate limiting at transport level** — per-target, not just per-trust-level\n- **BLE transport** — v0.7\n- **LoRa/Meshtastic transport** — v0.8\n- **DiscoveryController extraction** — v0.7 when node needs active peer discovery for BLE\n- **Relay logging/observability** — structured relay-specific logging (future: relay metrics endpoint)\n\n---\n\n## Success criteria\n\n- Alice (no Internet) sends to Charlie (external) via Bob (has Internet + relay mode)\n- Message delivered when Bob's relay queue processes it through tiered delivery\n- Bob can also discover Charlie on LAN and deliver directly (if Charlie is local)\n- Relay path visible in delivery status\n- Policy prevents Stranger peers from relaying through the node (default config)\n-