            "content": "# v0.6: LAN Relay — Design Spec\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-28\n**Milestone:** v0.6 — LAN Relay\n**Status:** Design (rev 3 — after Claude + Codex reviews)\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nRoute messages through LAN peers during partial Internet outages. A node in Personal Relay mode accepts envelopes from peers, stores them in a relay outbox, and delivers via configured Quorum targets (HTTP mailboxes, MQTT brokers).\n\nKey insight: the relay queue is an \"outbox without crypto.\" It reuses the same delivery state machine and retry logic as the client outbox. The only difference: no `inner_bytes`, no re-encryption, no DAG tracking — just opaque `envelope_bytes` → Quorum delivery.\n\n**Scope note:** This spec is broader than the original ROADMAP v0.6 description. The ROADMAP describes untrusted best-effort submit/store relays. This spec adds trust/contact rework (#179), discovery hardening (#102, #116), crate extraction (`reme-relay`), and node operating modes (#23) because these are foundational for safe relay behavior. The ROADMAP should be updated to reflect this expanded scope.\n\n---\n\n## Design decisions\n\n| Decision | Outcome | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Relay outbox structure | Generalize outbox with `OutboxOwnership` | Less duplication than a separate RelayOutbox; delivery state machine is identical |\n| Shared delivery logic | Extract into `reme-relay` crate | Node and client both need outbox tick + peer policy |\n| Node operating modes | Both Infrastructure + Personal Relay in v0.6 | Config toggle; different deployments need different behavior |\n| TrustLevel prerequisite | Yes, build first | Relay policy needs trust levels to make capability decisions |\n| Security hardening prerequisite | Yes (#102, #116) | Relay trusts client discovery results; discovery must be hardened first |\n| Peer policy | Configurable trust thresholds, not hardcoded | Network benefits from open relay; privacy-conscious users restrict it |\n| **v0.6 relay delivery** | **Quorum-only** (no Direct tier from node) | Node has no active peer discovery in v0.6; DiscoveryController stays in client app |\n| Node discovery in v0.6 | Advertise-only mDNS (#145) | Node broadcasts presence for client discovery, but does not discover/verify peers itself |\n| Direct-tier relay from node | Deferred to v0.7 | Requires DiscoveryController extraction — too much scope for v0.6 |\n| Fine-grained relay routing | Deferred | \"Relay only to node X\", \"no direct for relayed\" — additive, not needed for v0.6 |\n| BLE tier assignment | Contextual: Direct, relay, or BestEffort | No \"BLE mesh protocol\" — BLE relay is the same model as LAN HTTP relay |\n| ack_secret KDF change | Deferred to v0.7 | Needed for re-encryption (FLAG_DETACHED); v0.6 doesn't re-encrypt |\n| `auto_direct_known_contacts` migration | Deferred | Keep existing boolean in client config for v0.6; threshold-based `direct_deliver` is node-only for now |\n\n---\n\n## Crate extraction: `reme-relay`\n\n### Motivation\n\nPersonal Relay nodes need outbox tick + peer policy — currently in client-only code. Extracting a shared crate avoids duplication and keeps delivery logic in one place.\n\n### What moves where\n\n| Current location | What | Destination |\n|---|---|---|\n| `reme-core` Client | `process_urgent_retries()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `process_maintenance()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `tiered_outbox_tick()` | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| `reme-core` Client | `tiered_config` field | `reme-relay` DeliveryEngine |\n| New | `RelayPolicy` + `TrustThreshold` | `reme-relay` |\n| New | `TrustLevel` enum | `reme-relay` (shared type) |\n| New | `TrustResolver` trait | `reme-relay` (reme-storage implements it) |\n| New | `OutboxOwnership` enum | `reme-outbox` |\n| `reme-core` Client | `prepare_message()`, crypto, DAG, tombstones | Stays in `reme-core` |\n| `apps/client/src/discovery/` | `DiscoveryController` | Stays in client app for v0.6 |\n\n### Proposed crate graph\n\n```\nreme-relay (NEW — shared delivery engine + policy types)\n├── reme-transport (TransportCoordinator, targets, delivery config)\n├── reme-outbox (generalized: Own vs Relay entries)\n│   NOTE: does NOT depend on reme-storage or reme-discovery.\n│   TrustLevel and TrustResolver trait live in reme-relay.\n│   Storage layers implement TrustResolver.\n\nreme-core (Client API — crypto + user-facing logic)\n├── reme-relay (delivery engine)\n├── reme-encryption (encrypt/decrypt)\n├── reme-message (wire formats)\n├── reme-storage (implements TrustResolver)\n└── Client-specific: prepare_message(), send_text_tiered(), DAG tracking,\n    tombstone handling, message decryption, DiscoveryController\n\nreme-node-core (Node API — mailbox + relay)\n├── reme-relay (delivery engine) ← NEW dependency\n├── reme-storage (MailboxStore + implements TrustResolver)\n├── reme-message\n└── Node-specific: mailbox storage, operating mode toggle,\n    HTTP API handlers, gossip replication (Infrastructure mode)\n```\n\n`reme-relay` does NOT depend on `reme-storage` or `reme-discovery`. The `TrustLevel` enum and `TrustResolver` trait live in `reme-relay`. Both `reme-core` and `reme-node-core` provide a `TrustResolver` implementation backed by their storage layer.\n\n### TrustResolver trait\n\n```rust\n/// Trait for looking up a peer's trust level.\n/// Implemented by storage layers in both client and node.\npub trait TrustResolver: Send + Sync {\n    /// Look up trust level for a peer by PublicID.\n    /// Returns Stranger if the peer is not in contacts.\n    fn resolve_trust(&self, peer_id: &PublicID) -> TrustLevel;\n\n    /// Look up trust level for a peer by routing key.\n    /// Used when only routing_key is available (e.g., from OuterEnvelope).\n    /// Returns Stranger if no contact matches.\n    fn resolve_trust_by_routing_key(&self, routing_key: &RoutingKey) -> TrustLevel;\n}\n```\n\n### DeliveryEngine\n\n```rust\n/// Shared delivery engine used by both Client and Node (Personal Relay mode).\n/// Drives the outbox tick loop: urgent retries, maintenance refreshes, expiry.\npub struct DeliveryEngine<S: OutboxStore> {\n    coordinator: Arc<TransportCoordinator>,\n    outbox: Outbox<S>,\n    config: TieredDeliveryConfig,\n}\n\nimpl<S: OutboxStore> DeliveryEngine<S> {\n    /// Combined tick: expire messages, process urgent retries, run maintenance.\n    /// Ownership-aware: relay entries skip Phase 2 maintenance.\n    pub async fn tick(&self) -> Result<TickResult, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Process urgent retries for messages that haven't reached quorum.\n    pub async fn process_urgent_retries(&self) -> Result<Vec<RetryResult>, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Process maintenance refreshes for distributed messages (Own entries only).\n    pub async fn process_maintenance(&self) -> Result<usize, DeliveryError>;\n\n    /// Enqueue an envelope for relay delivery (no inner_bytes, no DAG).\n    /// Deduplicates on (routing_key, message_id) — idempotent.\n    /// source_target is excluded from egress to prevent echo loops.\n    pub fn enqueue_relay(\n        &self,\n        routing_key: RoutingKey,\n        message_id: MessageID,\n        envelope_bytes: &[u8],\n        ttl_ms: Option<u64>,\n        source_target: Option<TargetId>,\n    ) -> Result<OutboxEntryId, DeliveryError>;\n}\n```\n\nThe Client wraps DeliveryEngine and adds crypto (`prepare_message()` → `engine.outbox.enqueue()` with `Ownership::Own`). The Node uses `engine.enqueue_relay()` directly.\n\nNote: `ClientOutbox` is renamed to `Outbox` (or `DeliveryOutbox`) since it now serves both client and node.\n\n---\n\n## Contact model rework (#179)\n\n### TrustLevel enum\n\nDefined in `reme-relay` (shared type), not in `reme-storage`:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, PartialOrd, Ord, Serialize, Deserialize)]\n#[repr(u8)]\npub enum TrustLevel {\n    Stranger = 0,   // Auto-created from incoming message, or unknown peer\n    Known = 1,      // Manually added, not verified\n    Verified = 2,   // Identity confirmed (LAN challenge-response, QR, out-of-band)\n    Trusted = 3,    // User-designated trusted contact\n}\n```\n\n`PartialOrd`/`Ord` derived so threshold comparisons work naturally: `peer.trust_level >= policy.relay_for`.\n\n### Contact struct (in reme-storage)\n\n```rust\npub struct Contact {\n    pub id: i64,\n    pub public_id: PublicID,\n    pub routing_key: RoutingKey,      // derived from public_id, persisted for indexing\n    pub name: Option<String>,\n    pub trust_level: TrustLevel,\n    pub verified_at: Option<i64>,     // unix timestamp of last verification\n    pub created_at: i64,\n}\n```\n\n### Schema migration\n\n```sql\n-- Step 1: Add columns (DEFAULT 0 = Stranger for new auto-created rows)\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN routing_key BLOB;\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN trust_level INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0;\nALTER TABLE contacts ADD COLUMN verified_at INTEGER;\n\n-- Step 2: Backfill existing contacts as Known (they were manually added)\nUPDATE contacts SET trust_level = 1;\n\n-- Step 3: Index for routing_key lookups (relay policy, message routing)\nCREATE INDEX idx_contacts_routing_key ON contacts(routing_key);\n```\n\n### Integration points\n\n- `Client::add_contact()` — default `Known` for manual adds\n- Auto-created from incoming messages — `Stranger`\n- `DiscoveryController` verification success — upgrade to `Verified` + set `verified_at`\n- `Client::set_trust_level()` — user-initiated trust changes\n- `TrustResolver` impl in `reme-storage::Storage` — queries contacts table\n\n---\n\n## Peer capability policy\n\n### Two policy axes for v0.6\n\n| Policy | Controls | Question it answers |\n|---|---|---|\n| `accept_from` | HTTP POST /api/v1/submit | \"Who can push envelopes into my mailbox?\" |\n| `relay_for` | Relay queue → Quorum delivery | \"Whose envelopes do I forward via my transports?\" |\n\n`direct_deliver` (the third axis from earlier brainstorming) is deferred. In v0.6, nodes relay to Quorum only — no Direct-tier delivery from nodes. The client's existing `auto_direct_known_contacts` boolean continues to control client-side Direct-tier behavior unchanged.\n\n### Configuration\n\n```toml\n[node]\nmode = \"infrastructure\"  # \"infrastructure\" or \"personal_relay\"\n\n[node.personal_relay]\n# Quorum delivery settings for relay outbox\nquorum = { count = 2 }\nurgent_initial_delay_secs = 5\nurgent_max_delay_secs = 300\ntick_interval_secs = 5\n\n# Relay outbox limits\nmax_relay_entries = 10000\nmax_relay_bytes = 52428800  # 50 MiB\nrelay_max_ttl_hours = 168   # 7 days cap regardless of envelope TTL\n\n[node.personal_relay.policy]\n# Trust level thresholds (\"any\", \"known+\", \"verified+\", \"trusted\", \"none\")\naccept_from = \"any\"           # default: accept from everyone\nrelay_for = \"verified+\"       # default: relay for verified and trusted contacts\n\n# Per-trust-level rate limits (requests per minute, 0 = unlimited)\n[node.personal_relay.rate_limits]\nstranger = 5\nknown = 30\nverified = 100\ntrusted = 0\n```\n\n### Default policy table\n\n| TrustLevel | accept_from=any | relay_for=verified+ |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stranger | Yes (rate-limited 5/min) | No |\n| Known | Yes (rate-limited 30/min) | No |\n| Verified | Yes (100/min) | Yes |\n| Trusted | Yes (unlimited) | Yes |\n\n### Trust resolution at submit time\n\nWhen a peer submits an envelope via HTTP POST `/api/v1/submit`, the node determines the submitter's trust level:\n\n| Scenario | How identified | TrustLevel |\n|---|---|---|\n| Anonymous POST (no auth) | IP only, no identity | Stranger |\n| Signed replication header with known contact PublicID | Signature verification → contact lookup | Contact's TrustLevel |\n| Signed replication header with unknown PublicID | Valid signature but not in contacts | Stranger |\n| mDNS-discovered peer (identity verified by client) | Client verified, node sees signed header | Contact's TrustLevel |\n\nFor v0.6, the node itself does NOT perform mDNS peer discovery/verification. The *client* discovers and verifies peers via mDNS, then submits envelopes to the node. The node identifies the submitter via signed replication headers and looks up trust from contacts.\n\n### RelayPolicy struct\n\n```rust\npub struct RelayPolicy {\n    pub accept_from: TrustThreshold,\n    pub relay_for: TrustThreshold,\n    pub rate_limits: PerTrustRateLimits,\n    pub max_relay_entries: usize,\n    pub max_relay_bytes: u64,\n    pub relay_max_ttl_ms: u64,\n}\n\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy)]\npub enum TrustThreshold {\n    None,         // disabled\n    Any,          // all peers including strangers\n    KnownPlus,    // Known, Verified, Trusted\n    VerifiedPlus, // Verified, Trusted\n    TrustedOnly,  // Trusted only\n}\n\nimpl TrustThreshold {\n    pub fn allows(&self, level: TrustLevel) -> bool {\n        match self {\n            Self::None => false,\n            Self::Any => true,\n            Self::KnownPlus => level >= TrustLevel::Known,\n            Self::VerifiedPlus => level >= TrustLevel::Verified,\n            Self::TrustedOnly => level >= TrustLevel::Trusted,\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Node operating modes (#23)\n\n### Behavior differences\n\n| Aspect | Infrastructure | Personal Relay |\n|---|---|---|\n| Inbound envelopes | Store in mailbox | Store in mailbox + enqueue in relay outbox |\n| Outbound delivery | Fire-and-forget gossip (`ReplicationClient`) | Quorum delivery via `DeliveryEngine` |\n| Persistence | Mailbox only | Mailbox + relay outbox |\n| Retry logic | None | 2-phase: Urgent → Relayed (see state machine) |\n| Discovery | None | Advertise-only mDNS (#145) |\n| Use case | Public mailbox serving many users | Home server, personal relay, gateway |\n\n### Implementation\n\n```rust\nenum NodeMode {\n    Infrastructure {\n        replication: ReplicationClient,\n    },\n    PersonalRelay {\n        engine: DeliveryEngine<SqliteOutboxStore>,\n        policy: RelayPolicy,\n        trust: Arc<dyn TrustResolver>,\n    },\n}\n```\n\nOn envelope receipt:\n- **Infrastructure**: `mailbox.store()` + `replication.broadcast()` (fire-and-forget)\n- **Personal Relay**: `mailbox.store()` + policy check + `engine.enqueue_relay()` (persistent, Quorum delivery)\n\n---\n\n## Outbox generalization\n\n### OutboxOwnership\n\n```rust\npub enum OutboxOwnership {\n    /// Our own message — has inner_bytes for potential re-encryption (v1.0)\n    Own,\n    /// Relaying for someone else — opaque envelope only\n    Relay,\n}\n```\n\n### OutboxStore trait changes\n\nThe current `outbox_enqueue()` requires `PublicID` and `ContentId` — relay entries have neither (can't derive PublicID from RoutingKey, ContentId is inside encrypted InnerEnvelope).\n\n**New method** added to the trait:\n\n```rust\n/// Add a relay entry to the outbox.\n///\n/// Unlike `outbox_enqueue`, this only requires routing_key and message_id\n/// (available from OuterEnvelope without decryption).\n/// Deduplicates on (routing_key, message_id) — idempotent.\nfn outbox_enqueue_relay(\n    &self,\n    routing_key: RoutingKey,\n    message_id: MessageID,\n    envelope_bytes: &[u8],\n    expires_at_ms: Option<u64>,\n    source_target: Option<TargetId>,\n) -> Result<OutboxEntryId, Self::Error>;\n\n/// Get relay entries due for retry (Urgent phase, not Relayed/Expired).\nfn outbox_get_relay_retry_due(&self, now_ms: u64) -> Result<Vec<PendingMessage>, Self::Error>;\n```\n\n**Existing methods that need ownership-conditional behavior:**\n\n| Method | Own entries | Relay entries |\n|---|---|---|\n| `outbox_get_by_content_id()` | Works (content_id is set) | N/A — never called for relay (content_id is None) |\n| `outbox_get_for_recipient()` | Works (recipient is set) | N/A — relay entries use routing_key |\n| `outbox_get_maintenance_due()` | Returns Own entries in Distributed phase | Skips Relay entries (no maintenance phase) |\n| `outbox_get_urgent_retry_due()` | Returns Own entries in Urgent phase | Use `outbox_get_relay_retry_due()` instead |\n| `outbox_mark_confirmed()` | Sets `Confirmed` (recipient ACK) | Sets `Relayed` (quorum handoff) |\n\n### Schema changes\n\n```sql\n-- Add ownership column\nALTER TABLE outbox_entries ADD COLUMN ownership INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0;\n-- 0 = Own, 1 = Relay\n\n-- Add routing_key column (relay entries don't have PublicID)\nALTER TABLE outbox_entries ADD COLUMN routing_key BLOB;\n\n-- Add source_target column (for loop prevention in relay)\nALTER TABLE outbox_entries ADD COLUMN source_target TEXT;\n\n-- Backfill routing_key from existing recipient PublicIDs\n-- (application-level migration, not pure SQL)\n\n-- Dedup index for relay entries\nCREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_outbox_relay_dedup\n    ON outbox_entries(routing_key, message_id)\n    WHERE ownership = 1;\n```\n\nThe `recipient` (PublicID) column is **nullable** for relay entries (set to NULL, not zeroed bytes). The `content_id` column is **nullable** for relay entries. No sentinel values — proper NULLs are cleaner and don't risk false matches on queries.\n\n### PendingMessage changes\n\n```rust\npub struct PendingMessage {\n    pub id: OutboxEntryId,\n    pub recipient: Option<PublicID>,    // None for relay entries\n    pub routing_key: RoutingKey,        // always available\n    pub content_id: Option<ContentId>,  // None for relay entries\n    pub ownership: OutboxOwnership,\n    pub envelope_bytes: Vec<u8>,\n    pub inner_bytes: Vec<u8>,           // empty for relay entries\n    pub source_target: Option<TargetId>, // excluded from egress (loop prevention)\n    pub created_at_ms: u64,\n    pub expires_at_ms: Option<u64>,\n    pub expired_at_ms: Option<u64>,\n    pub attempts: Vec<TransportAttempt>,\n    pub next_retry_at_ms: Option<u64>,\n    pub confirmation: Option<DeliveryConfirmation>,\n    pub successful_targets: HashSet<TargetId>,\n    pub tiered_phase: TieredDeliveryPhase,\n}\n```\n\n### Relay-specific behavior\n\n- **No DAG tracking**: Relay entries don't update sender DAG state. `content_id` is None.\n- **No re-encryption**: `inner_bytes` is empty; can't re-encrypt for different transport.\n- **TTL from envelope**: Relay entries use `min(envelope.ttl_hours, relay_max_ttl_hours)`. If envelope has no TTL (`None`), use `relay_max_ttl_hours` as default. Reject relay submissions with no TTL and no configured default (defensive).\n- **Deduplication**: `enqueue_relay()` deduplicates on `(routing_key, message_id)` via unique index. If entry already exists, returns existing `OutboxEntryId` (idempotent).\n- **Backpressure**: `enqueue_relay()` checks `max_relay_entries` and `max_relay_bytes` limits. Returns `Err(RelayQueueFull)` if exceeded. See HTTP response handling below.\n- **Loop prevention**: `source_target` is stored with the relay entry and excluded from egress target set during delivery. Prevents echoing the envelope back to its submitter.\n\n### Relay state machine (2-phase with distinct terminal state)\n\nRelay entries use a distinct terminal state `Relayed` — NOT `Confirmed`. `Confirmed` means \"recipient acknowledged via DAG/tombstone\" and is semantically incorrect for relay handoff.\n\n```\nPhase 1 (Urgent): Aggressive retry until quorum reached\n    │\n    ├─ Quorum reached → Relayed\n    │   Relay responsibility satisfied: \"I got this to enough infrastructure nodes.\"\n    │   Cleanup after configurable delay.\n    │\n    └─ TTL expired → Expired\n        Best-effort delivery exhausted.\n```\n\nNo Phase 2 (Distributed/maintenance) for relay entries because:\n1. The relay node can't confirm recipient receipt (no DAG visibility)\n2. Once quorum is reached, infrastructure nodes are responsible for serving the message\n3. Periodic re-submission would waste bandwidth for messages the relay has no stake in\n\n### TieredDeliveryPhase extension\n\n```rust\npub enum TieredDeliveryPhase {\n    Urgent,\n    Distributed { confidence, reached_at_ms, last_maintenance_ms },\n    Confirmed { confirmed_at_ms },\n    /// Relay handoff complete — quorum reached for a relayed envelope.\n    /// Distinct from Confirmed (which means recipient ACK).\n    Relayed { relayed_at_ms: u64 },\n}\n```\n\nThe `DeliveryEngine` checks `ownership` when transitioning phases:\n- `Own` entries: Urgent → Distributed → Confirmed (existing 3-phase)\n- `Relay` entries: Urgent → Relayed (2-phase, skip Distributed)\n\n---\n\n## Relay flow (Personal Relay mode)\n\n```\nPeer submits envelope via HTTP POST /api/v1/submit\n    │\n    ├─ Resolve peer TrustLevel:\n    │   - Signed replication header → contact lookup by PublicID\n    │   - Anonymous → Stranger\n    │\n    ├─ Rate limit check (per TrustLevel)\n    │   - Exceeded → 429 Too Many Requests\n    │\n    ├─ accept_from threshold check\n    │   - Below threshold → 403 Forbidden\n    │\n    ├─ Node stores in mailbox (always succeeds independently)\n    │   → 200 OK with { \"stored\": true, \"relayed\": ... }\n    │\n    └─ relay_for threshold check\n        │\n        ├─ Below threshold → { \"relayed\": false, \"reason\": \"policy\" }\n        │\n        └─ Passes → Backpressure check\n            │\n            ├─ Queue full → { \"relayed\": false, \"reason\": \"queue_full\" }\n            │   (mailbox storage succeeded; relay is best-effort)\n            │\n            └─ OK → DeliveryEngine.enqueue_relay(\n                │       routing_key, message_id, envelope_bytes,\n                │       ttl_ms, source_target\n                │   )\n                │   Deduplicates on (routing_key, message_id).\n                │   source_target excluded from egress.\n                │   → { \"relayed\": true }\n                │\n                └─ Outbox tick loop:\n                    └─ Quorum: forward to configured HTTP mailboxes / MQTT\n                       (excluding source_target)\n```\n\n**Key invariant:** Mailbox storage and relay admission are independent. Mailbox always stores (if `accept_from` passes). Relay is best-effort on top. The HTTP response body indicates both outcomes so the caller knows whether relay was attempted.\n\n**Intermittent connectivity:** If the relay node loses Internet, the outbox tick loop retries in Phase 1 with exponential backoff (5s → 10s → ... → 300s cap). When connectivity returns, queued relay entries are delivered.\n\n---\n\n## Node discovery scope (#145)\n\nFor v0.6, node mDNS is **advertise-only**:\n- Node broadcasts its presence (`_reme._tcp.local.`) with `caps=relay,store` in TXT records\n- Clients discover the node and can submit envelopes to it\n- Node does NOT actively discover or verify other peers\n- Node does NOT register ephemeral Direct-tier targets\n\nThe `DiscoveryController` (peer matching, verification, target registration) stays in `apps/client/`. Extraction into a shared crate is deferred to v0.7 when the node needs active peer discovery for BLE relay.\n\n### mDNS TXT record extension\n\nCurrent TXT schema: `v=1`, `rk=<routing_key_hex>`, `port=<http_port>`.\n\nv0.6 adds a `caps` key:\n\n```\ncaps=relay          # accepts envelopes for relay\ncaps=relay,store    # accepts envelopes for relay + persistent storage\n```\n\nComma-separated capability tokens. Forward-compatible for v0.7+.\n\n---\n\n## Security hardening prerequisites\n\n### #102: Enforce public_id on direct peers\n\nScope Tier 1 routing so that direct delivery only targets peers whose `public_id` matches the message's `routing_key`. The fix: `TransportCoordinator` enforces `target.config().can_serve(&envelope.routing_key)` — already partially implemented, needs enforcement.\n\n### #116: Channel binding for identity challenge-response\n\nThe current LAN identity verification (`GET /api/v1/identity?challenge=<base64>`) doesn't bind the proof to the transport channel. Fix: include transport-layer binding (e.g., ephemeral connection nonce) in the signed challenge response.\n\n---\n\n## Dependency graph\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n    subgraph \"Layer 0: Prerequisites (independent)\"\n        A179[\"#179 TrustLevel + Contact rework\"]\n        A102[\"#102 public_id enforcement\"]\n        A116[\"#116 channel binding\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 0: Parallel (independent)\"\n        A145[\"#145 node mDNS (advertise-only)\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 1: Foundation\"\n        B1[\"reme-relay crate extraction\"]\n        B2[\"Outbox generalization (Own vs Relay)\"]\n        B75[\"#75 Peer capability policy\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 2: Relay\"\n        C23[\"#23 Node operating modes\"]\n        C2[\"Relay queue ingress + HTTP response\"]\n        C3[\"Relay queue egress (Quorum)\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph \"Layer 3: Integration\"\n        D1[\"Integration tests\"]\n        D2[\"Documentation + ROADMAP update\"]\n    end\n\n    A179 --> B1\n    A179 --> B2\n    A179 --> B75\n    A102 --> B1\n    A116 --> B1\n    B1 --> C23\n    B2 --> C2\n    B75 --> C2\n    B75 --> C3\n    C23 --> C2\n    C23 --> C3\n    A145 --> D1\n    C2 --> D1\n    C3 --> D1\n    D1 --> D2\n```\n\nNote: #145 (advertise-only mDNS) is parallel work, not a prerequisite for relay. It enables clients to discover nodes for submission, but the relay queue itself doesn't depend on it.\n\n---\n\n## Deferred from v0.6\n\n- **Direct-tier relay from nodes** — requires DiscoveryController extraction (v0.7)\n- **`direct_deliver` policy axis** — node needs active discovery first (v0.7)\n- **`auto_direct_known_contacts` → threshold migration** — client config change, wider than relay scope\n- **ack_secret deterministic KDF** — needed for re-encryption in v0.7\n- **FLAG_DETACHED re-encryption** — v0.7 when BLE arrives\n- **Fine-grained relay routing** — \"relay only to node X\", \"no direct for relayed\"\n- **BLE transport** — v0.7\n- **LoRa/Meshtastic transport** — v0.8\n- **DiscoveryController extraction** — v0.7\n- **Relay logging/observability** — structured relay metrics endpoint\n\n---\n\n## Success criteria\n\n**Functional:**\n- Alice (no Internet) sends to Charlie (external) via Bob (has Internet + relay mode)\n- Message delivered when Bob's relay queue forwards to Quorum\n- Policy prevents Stranger peers from relaying through the node (default config)\n- Node operating mode toggle works (Infrastructure vs Personal Relay)\n- Relay outbox persists across node restarts\n\n**Correctness:**\n- Duplicate envelope submissions are idempotent (no double-relay)\n- Source-target exclusion prevents relay echo loops\n- Relay outbox respects size limits; queue-full does not fail mailbox storage\n- Intermittent connectivity: relay queue retries and delivers when Internet returns\n- Mixed Own/Relay entries in outbox don't interfere with each other\n- `Relayed` state is distinct from `Confirmed` — no semantic corruption\n\n**Integration tests:**\n- Relay round-trip: client → node (relay) → quorum node → recipient client\n- Dedup: same envelope submitted twice → relayed once\n- Policy: stranger rejected from relay, verified accepted\n- Loop prevention: relayed envelope not echoed back to source\n- Backpressure: queue full → mailbox stored, relay rejected, clear response\n- Restart persistence: relay entries survive node restart\n- TTL: relay entries expire correctly (envelope TTL capped by policy)\n",
