            "new_string": "**Scope note:** This milestone is broader than the original ROADMAP description. It adds trust/contact rework, discovery hardening, crate extraction, and node operating modes as foundations for safe relay behavior. ROADMAP will be updated to reflect the expanded scope.\n\n### Architecture overview\n\nThe relay queue is an \"outbox without crypto\" — same delivery state machine, no `inner_bytes`/DAG/re-encryption. `OutboxOwnership` (Own vs Relay) distinguishes client messages from relayed envelopes. A new `Relayed` terminal state (distinct from `Confirmed` = recipient ACK) represents \"quorum handoff complete.\"\n\nThe `reme-relay` crate extracts `DeliveryEngine` (tick loop, urgent retries, maintenance) from `reme-core`, plus `TrustLevel`, `TrustResolver` trait, and `RelayPolicy`. It does NOT depend on `reme-storage` or `reme-encryption`.\n\nv0.6 relay is **Quorum-only** — the node has no active peer discovery, so no Direct-tier delivery from nodes. `DiscoveryController` stays in the client app. Node mDNS (#145) is advertise-only.\n\nPeer policy has two axes: `accept_from` (who can submit) and `relay_for` (whose envelopes we forward). Both are configurable trust thresholds. Default: strangers can submit but not relay.\n\nLoop prevention: `source_target` stored with each relay entry and excluded from egress target set. Backpressure: `max_relay_entries` + `max_relay_bytes` limits; queue-full does not fail mailbox storage. TTL: `min(envelope.ttl_hours, relay_max_ttl)`, None defaults to `relay_max_ttl`.",
